During a press briefing, White House Press Secretary Karine Jean-Pierre made several announcements and addressed various topics. She announced that President Biden will sign a proclamation to establish the Emmett Till and Mamie Till Mobley National Monument in Illinois and Mississippi. The monument will protect places that tell the story of Emmett Till's life and racially motivated murder, as well as the activism of his mother, Mamie Till Mobley. Jean-Pierre also discussed Russia's bombardment of the Ukrainian city of Odesa and expressed concern that Russia may expand its targeting of Ukrainian grain facilities and civilian ships. She urged Russia to stop targeting food supplies and return to the Black Sea Grain Initiative. Additionally, Jean-Pierre announced that the First Lady will raise the flag for the United States at the UNESCO headquarters in Paris to show the country's commitment to international cooperation. She also mentioned the upcoming meeting between President Biden and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, stating that the timing is still being determined. In response to questions, Jean-Pierre addressed issues related to Israel, the Texas governor's actions at the border, Private King's situation, and the former President's comments. She emphasized the administration's commitment to civil rights, protecting history, and addressing immigration in a humane way.